\begin_layout Standard
[Variation in conditions] We inspect how consumption varies in the economy
 with respect to the differences in prosperity that exist both within a
 geographical reference area and across geographical areas spread through
 the economy.
 Within a certain areas of reference, any improvement in prosperity for
 the consumer is contingent on her occupational or educational status, the
 inheritable wealth and the positive externality or affluence associated
 with being in the area of reference itself.
 Given that all else being equal, a consumer better equipped with educational
 or occupational status and a social network of more richer consumers is
 better prepared for higher prosperity, we contrast the educational and
 occupational expenditures against the consumption on assets (durable goods)
 and non-durable consumption in Nigeria and Tanzania.
 The comparison of consumption across the two countries essentially tracks
 the consumer's preparedness to be in a improved surrounding area as the
 educational and occupational expenditure - while considering the current
 characteristics of the consumer - including the educational, occupational
 levels as well as the assets owned by the consumer.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Such an analysis is of interest for two reasons.
 First, such consumer characteristics can also result a certain inertia
 - i.e.
 consumers with a certain level of needs, assets and educational/occupational
 level may not move away to a poorer reference.
 This influences the how a desire for relative prosperity may be outpaced
 by extreme differences in reference areas.
 Second, the distribution of educational and occupational skills across
 the economy determines access to consumer markets in the economy and has
 a direct influence on the quality of consumption.
 The control for inequality in prosperity across across geographical reference
 thus helps us better understand how consumption differs across multiple
 economics.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While out of scope of the current chapter, the above may have implications
 for both migration pressures and the notions of status consumption in an
 economy.
 More specifically, the consumers preference to remain in a poorer reference
 if they enjoy relative affluence needs to be qualified in light of extremely
 sparse distribution of economic opportunities in the economy.
 When a poorer reference may have less opportunities both for mobility and
 status consumption, then the escape to a richer reference may be more than
 the chance the improve one's immediate income - but an access to improbable
 mobility.
\end_layout

